 \n \n Using the rule in a  Data Structure   Rule Set : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/555d479c0b5848467b9e8754cb062b847a0057b3.png]\nDescription: The image displays a hierarchical tree structure related to \u0022Task\u0022 management in a user interface. The main category is labeled \u0022Task,\u0022 which expands to include subcategories: \u0022Entities,\u0022 \u0022Filter Sets,\u0022 and \u0022Rule Sets.\u0022 Within \u0022Rule Sets,\u0022 there is a further expansion labeled \u0022Dates,\u0022 which includes an entry titled \u0022ComputeDaysToDueDate.\u0022 The \u0022ComputeDaysToDueDate\u0022 category expands to show a sub-item labeled \u0022Dependencies,\u0022 which additionally contains an item titled \u0022Task_DueDate.\u0022 This structure appears to facilitate organizing and managing tasks and rules associated with due dates and dependencies in a software application.\n\n\n  \n  Dependencies  is list of fields which on change trigger the execution of the rule, in this case change of the field DueDate in the Task entity ( Task_DueDate ). \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/84b29ee591eaf686bfc1447379f5e19ee39a057c.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a rule configuration titled \u0022ComputeDaysToDueDate.\u0022 In the top section labeled \u0022(Info) (Schema Item),\u0022 it shows fields for Ancestors, Inheritable status as False, and the Name \u0022ComputeDaysToDueDate.\u0022 The Misc section contains various parameters: ConditionRule is set to \u0022SR_Task_Status_Not Done,\u0022 Entity is listed as \u0022Task,\u0022 and EntityName is also \u0022Task.\u0022 The Priority is marked as 100, while RuleDependencies is categorized as a \u0022Collection.\u0022 Additionally, it defines TargetField as \u0022DaysToDueDate\u0022 and ValueRule as \u0022ComputeDaysToDueDate.\u0022 This interface appears to be part of a rule management system aimed at calculating the number of days until a task\u0027s due date based on specified conditions.\n\n\n  \n Notes: \n \n  ConditionRule  specifies the condition under which this rule will be applied (see the next chapter) \n  Entity  links the rule to a data entity \n  TargetField  determines the entity field that will be filled with the rule result \u2014 in this case, the number of remaining days; here we use a virtual field that is not saved to the database \n  ValueRule  is simply a reference to the rule definition \n \n Here is a simple schema of all the model elements used: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/65ef1384fbd715a206a08ef0df02f43c8e01c172.png]\nDescription: The image presents a conceptual diagram illustrating the relationships between data, user interface (UI), and business logic elements in a system. The \u0022DATA\u0022 section includes terms like Data structure, Entity, Rule set, Rule, Dependency, Database entity, Virtual field, and Database field. The \u0022UI\u0022 section lists Screen and Screen section. Under \u0022BUSINESS LOGIC,\u0022 it contains the term Simple data rule. Arrows connect these elements, indicating dependencies and interactions among them, suggesting a structured overview of how data, UI, and business logic are integrated within a system.\n\n\n  \n Using this rule and the corresponding data structure, we can, for example, add a column named \u201CDays to Due Date\u201D to the Task data view: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/711cd62b712454ac49d2330635f54f14fe71e996.png]\nDescription: The image displays a table titled \u0022Tasks,\u0022 containing a list of various tasks and their associated details. The columns include \u0022Name,\u0022 \u0022Description,\u0022 \u0022Status,\u0022 \u0022Priority,\u0022 \u0022Due date,\u0022 \u0022Assigned to,\u0022 and \u0022Days to Due Date.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","l